"FAQPage", "mainEntity": [{"@type": "Question", "name": "What is Blockchain in simple terms?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Blockchain is a decentralized system for securely recording transactions. Think of it as a digital ledger shared across a network of computers (or nodes). Instead of relying on one institution (like a bank or government) to record transactions, blockchain uses these nodes to validate and store the data. Each time a transaction occurs, it\u2019s grouped into a block. Once the block is verified by the network, it\u2019s linked to the previous one, creating a chain of data or transactions."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "What is Blockchain mainly used for?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Banks use blockchain for international payments, fraud prevention, and transparent trading. In healthcare, blockchain is improving data security, patient privacy, and the sharing of medical records. Blockchain is having a huge impact on supply chains by making it easier to track products every step of the way. Real estate companies are using blockchain to streamline property transactions, making them faster, more transparent, and more secure. Blockchain is changing media and advertising by improving transparency and cutting down on fraud. And more!"}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "What are the pros and cons of Blockchain?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Pros: Tamper-proof Speedy transactions Built to last Trustworthy Lower costs Cons: Ownership Data modifications Infrastructure challenges Storage issues Security vulnerabilities"}}]}]

It\u2019s widely used in a number of different web frameworks including Bootstrap, Django, and Ruby on Rails."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "How does Sass work?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "The way CSS preprocessors work is that they allow you to write a modified form of CSS, and then that modified version of the code is interpreted by a compiler that transforms it into regular CSS so that your web browser can read and understand it. You can think of this as writing flexible, human-readable CSS code, which a CSS preprocessor then converts into something a computer can read and execute."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "What is the difference between Sass and CSS?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "CSS preprocessors, like Sass, allow developers to write less repetitive code. The main differences between Sass and CSS are in their features. While Sass has the extra functionality of using variables, nesting, mixins, and more, CSS doesn\u2019t. Where CSS would eat up your time by rewriting the same codes over and over and over again, Sass helps save time by reducing repetition."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Why do people use Sass instead of CSS?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Developers of all types use Sass instead of CSS in order to have a process for writing CSS code that is more efficient and easier to maintain. Where CSS would eat up your time by rewriting the same codes over and over and over again, Sass helps save time by reducing repetition."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Should I learn CSS or Sass?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Sass, like all CSS preprocessors, is an extension of CSS. That means that in order to write Sass and utilize it in your web applications you need to have a thorough understanding of CSS. In other words, you would not be able to write Sass without first knowing CSS."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Should I learn Sass after CSS?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes, Sass is an extension of CSS and in order to write Sass and utilize it in your web applications you need to have a thorough understanding of CSS."}}]}]
